sentences: Mike Elliott is a saxophonist who was born in Jamaica on 6 August 1929.
They played on early 1960s Jamaican Ska recordings issued on the Planetone label such as "Hitch & Scramble" (recorded in 1962).
He had also recorded a handful of records under his own name, two of them on the Planetone label in 1963.

His recording "This Love of Mine" appeared on the flip side of Terry Moon's "Moon Man" and it would actually appear again later appear on the Carnival label in 1964 as the flip side to Young Satchmo's "Things Are Getting Better".
By 1967 he was a member of the multi-racial English soul group The Foundations who had million selling hits with "Baby, Now That I've Found You" and "Build Me Up Buttercup" etc.
He also played on their PYE debut album "From The Foundations", a live album "Rocking The Foundations" and on three Foundations tracks at a John Peel session in January 1968.

In 1968 The Foundations were experiencing some problems within their group as well as problems with their songwriter and producer Tony Macaulay who wouldn't allow them to record their own compositions.
In 1972 Elliott had a Reggae styled single, "Milk & Honey" released on the Ackee record label.
This was released on the label in 1971.
Terry Moon – "Moon Man" / Mike Elliot – "This Love of Mine" – Planetone RC11, 1963
Elliott – "J.K. Shuffle" – Planetone RC12, 1963
Mike Elliott – "This Love of Mine" / Young Satchmo – "Things Are Getting Better" – Carnival CV 7008, 1964
Mike Elliott – "Milk & Honey" / Mike Elliott & Errol – "Burst A Shirt" – Ackee ACK151, 1972
"This Love of Mine" appears on the various artists compilation – The Ska's The Limit – Carnival CX 1000
At 38 years of age he was the oldest member of the group and was nearly 20 years older than the youngest member of the group 18-year-old Tim Harris.
He played on ska recordings in the early 1960s and on pop and soul music hits in the late 1960s.
He is best known as a co-founding member of the British band The Foundations, and played on their hit singles "Baby, Now That I've Found You" and "Build Me Up Buttercup".
Early 1960s

By 1967 he was a member of the multi-racial English soul group The Foundations who had million selling hits with "Baby, Now That I've Found You" and "Build Me Up Buttercup" etc.
He played on their first three hit singles, "Baby, Now That I've Found You", "Back on My Feet Again" and "Any Old Time (You're Lonely And Sad)".
The songs were "Let It Fall" on side 1 and "Can't Change" on side 2.
"Tan Tan" Thornton and Sonny Burke had previously recorded with Denzil Dennis.
